### STEP 7 — Set Up Environment Files

In the root of your project, create these four files:

**`.env.local`** (used when you run `npm run dev`)
```
VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8080/api
VITE_APP_ENV=local
```

**`.env.development`**
```
VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://your-dev-backend.railway.app/api
VITE_APP_ENV=development
```

**`.env.staging`**
```
VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://your-staging-backend.railway.app/api
VITE_APP_ENV=staging
```

**`.env.production`**
```
VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://your-prod-backend.railway.app/api
VITE_APP_ENV=production
```

> **Important:** Add `.env.local` to your `.gitignore`. The other `.env.*` files can be committed since they contain no secrets — just URLs.

Update `.gitignore` to include:
```
.env.local
.env.*.local

STEP 8 — Update vite.config.js
Replace vite.config.js with:
jsimport { defineConfig } from 'vite'
import react from '@vitejs/plugin-react'

export default defineConfig({
  plugins: [react()],
  server: {
    port: 5173,
    proxy: {
      // Optional: proxy API calls in dev to avoid CORS issues
      '/api': {
        target: 'http://localhost:8080',
        changeOrigin: true,
      }
    }
  },
  build: {
    outDir: 'dist',
    sourcemap: false,
  }
})

STEP 9 — Build the Full Folder Structure
Run this block in your terminal to create all the folders and empty files at once:
bash# Create folder structure
mkdir -p src/api
mkdir -p src/components/common
mkdir -p src/components/analysis
mkdir -p src/context
mkdir -p src/hooks
mkdir -p src/pages/auth
mkdir -p src/pages/dashboard
mkdir -p src/pages/admin
mkdir -p src/router
mkdir -p src/utils

# Create empty files
touch src/api/axios.js
touch src/api/auth.api.js
touch src/api/merchant.api.js
touch src/api/analysis.api.js
touch src/api/admin.api.js

touch src/components/common/Button.jsx
touch src/components/common/Input.jsx
touch src/components/common/LoadingSpinner.jsx
touch src/components/common/ErrorMessage.jsx
touch src/components/common/Navbar.jsx
touch src/components/analysis/AnalysisCard.jsx
touch src/components/analysis/AnalysisHistory.jsx

touch src/context/AuthContext.jsx

touch src/hooks/useAuth.js
touch src/hooks/useApi.js

touch src/pages/auth/LoginPage.jsx
touch src/pages/auth/RegisterPage.jsx
touch src/pages/dashboard/DashboardPage.jsx
touch src/pages/dashboard/ProfilePage.jsx
touch src/pages/dashboard/AnalysisPage.jsx
touch src/pages/admin/AdminDashboard.jsx

touch src/router/AppRouter.jsx
touch src/router/ProtectedRoute.jsx

touch src/utils/storage.js

Windows users: Run this in Git Bash or WSL. In PowerShell, use New-Item instead of touch.

Windows PowerShell equivalent:
powershell$folders = @(
  "src/api", "src/components/common", "src/components/analysis",
  "src/context", "src/hooks", "src/pages/auth", "src/pages/dashboard",
  "src/pages/admin", "src/router", "src/utils"
)
$folders | ForEach-Object { New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path $_ }

STEP 10 — Wire Up the Router in App.jsx
Now update src/App.jsx to use React Router:
jsximport AppRouter from './router/AppRouter'

function App() {
  return <AppRouter />
}

export default App
Then populate src/router/AppRouter.jsx with the full router (copy from the architecture plan above — it's the complete AppRouter.jsx file with all routes).

STEP 11 — Test That Everything Works
bashnpm run dev
Open your browser at http://localhost:5173. You should see your app running. Tailwind will be active — try adding a className="text-blue-500" anywhere to confirm it's working.

STEP 12 — Add Useful npm Scripts
Open package.json and update the scripts section:
json"scripts": {
  "dev": "vite",
  "build": "vite build",
  "build:staging": "vite build --mode staging",
  "build:production": "vite build --mode production",
  "preview": "vite preview",
  "lint": "eslint . --ext js,jsx --report-unused-disable-directives --max-warnings 0"
}
```

Now you can run `npm run build:staging` and it'll pick up `.env.staging`.

